    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-18T12:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-18T12:29:00-05:00" n="368"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d368">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.77/402</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vologda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-18T20:00:00+02:31">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 18, 1918, 8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received May 26, 11.54 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>180. Conforming to the arrangement I made in Moscow an official of the Ways of
                    Communication [Ministry], in a special car, passed through Vologda yesterday to
                    meet <persName corresp="#p_ECH1">Emerson</persName>. Railway official is named
                    Lobanov whom I have known personally about a year, and who is very friendly. He
                    was discharged by the Soviet government but was reengaged about April 1. He
                    reports 42 per cent locomotives and great scarcity fuel [<hi rend="italic"
                        >sic</hi>]. Selections [says Russians?] do not see what American engineers
                    can accomplish with present railway working force; wired on my request to Moscow
                    for chief practical operating man to meet <persName corresp="#p_ECH1"
                        >Emerson</persName>, Vologda on arrival. <persName corresp="#p_ECH1"
                        >Emerson</persName> arrived at Vladivostok 7th, since which nothing from
                    Vladivostok but press says started west 13th.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
